column740:
15/May/25 6:38 PM;affan.baragazi@vodafone.com;Hi Krishnkumar, 
As mentioned in my earlier comment as well, the error is occurring because the link(LK_30003302) you're retrieving includes both a Mobile and a Cable customer. In Modes 2 and 3, the BanDetails field is mandatory for Mobile, so the request fails during the initial validation phase before it even reaches any downstream services. You can also confirm this in the screenshot below, which is taken from Confluence.

column742:
16/May/25 2:23 PM;affan.baragazi@vodafone.com;Hi [~pallavi.kokate1@vodafone.com],
According to this CR, if an error occurs under sublayer of GetCustomerDetails (in any API call failure towards other parties from OGW), call for any of the linked customer OGW will remove the specific customers from final response mapping. However, the error you're encountering in LegacySearch is not covered under this CR.
Also as mentioned in my earlier comments, the error _'One or more BAN and MarketCode combination must be populated in Mode #2'_ is triggered because the request fails during the initial validation phase before reaching any downstream services as BanDetails is mandatory for Mobile customers. From OGW's perspective, this behavior is aligned with the intended design.
Thanks;;;

15/May/25 6:39 PM;affan.baragazi@vodafone.com;Hi Krishnkumar, 
As mentioned in my earlier comment as well, the error is occurring because the link(LK_30003302) you're retrieving includes both a Mobile and a Cable customer. In Modes 2 and 3, the BanDetails field is mandatory for Mobile, so the request fails during the initial validation phase before it even reaches any downstream services. You can also confirm this in the screenshot below, which is taken from Confluence.
[https://confluence.sp.vodafone.com/display/OF/OGW+Service+3%3A+GetCustomerDetails]

column751:
16/May/25 2:22 PM;affan.baragazi@vodafone.com;Hi [~pallavi.kokate1@vodafone.com] ,
According to this CR, if an error occurs under sublayer of GetCustomerDetails (in any API call failure towards other parties from OGW), call for any of the linked customer OGW will remove the specific customers from final response mapping. However, the error you're encountering in LegacySearch is not covered under this CR. 
Also as mentioned in my earlier comments, the error _'One or more BAN and MarketCode combination must be populated in Mode #2'_ is triggered because the request fails during the initial validation phase before reaching any downstream services as BanDetails is mandatory for Mobile customers. From OGW's perspective, this behavior is aligned with the intended design.
Thanks;;;

column33:
We have observed that while placing new activation/Existing flows for all stacks, we are getting IBAN Validation error and not able to proceed the orders for Retail and Telesales channel.

*Steps to Reproduce for UM New activation flow:(Existing flow also IBAN error)*
 # Login to Omnius any channel in ACC1/ACC2
 # Search the address and check serviceability.
 # Once serviceability success click the cable option and select any cable/DSL/Mobile products in the list shown by configurator
 # Proceed with checkout.
 # Enter all the customer related information(Name, DOB, Email, Telephone number) and proceed further. 
 # Enter the IBAN and check IBAN validation done successfully and agent can able to proceed or we are getting error.

column737:
22/Apr/25 4:47 PM;ariadne.thun1@vodafone.com;Feedback from Simon Auch:

TL;DR: The issue observed by OSF (no products visible in configurator) was caused by an infrastructure component of the kubernetes cluster BLES runs in, not by BLES.

Requests from Omnius and IBP to BLES both had the issue that sometimes the request was rejected with a "401 unauthorized" error, returned by an nginx.

The path of a request from IBP/Omnius to BLES looks roughly like:
 * IBP/Omnius
 * ConHub
 * NGinx
 * BLES

The credentials for all requests to BLES are checked by the nginx instance directly in front of it and, therefore, this was not an issue with BLES.

Since the nginx checks the credentials and 401 errors are related to authorization, I checked the nginx logs. There I found errors indicating that one of the nginx pods (the nginx deployment consists of 3 pods) ran out of disk space. I then checked which pod was out of disk space and killed it, causing Kubernetes to reschedule a new pod to replace it. This fixed the issue.

Follow up steps I see for the infrastructure Teams:
 * improve monitoring for the nginx deployments
 * figure out why this pod was not detected as unhealthy by kubernetes on its own and change it
 * try to find out why the disk was full in the first place
 * retrospectively:
 ** why was it determined to not be an infrastructure issue?
 ** raise awareness for the criticality of cloud components in the system teams;;;

DXL Comments:-
Thank you Andreas.

My understanding so far is that DXL is sending 

External credit class= X

Expected:

External credit class= A

While checking the DXL logs, I found the traceID: 05ebb2da234bfe33d84c9dfc85de89a1

DXL is really  sending 
                                               <ns2:additionalData>
                                                               <ns2:key>externalCreditClass</ns2:key>
                                                               <ns2:value>X</ns2:value>
                                               </ns2:additionalData>

This DXL request is following this schufa rating response:
### POST SOUTHBOUND REST RESPONSE URI:http://js-schufa-rating-adapter.dxl-argocd/checkCreditStandingForCustomer WITH STATUS [200] ### {"state":"SUCCESS","infotext":["X- KI SCOREBEREICH I","ES LIEGEN KEINE DATEN AUS OEFFENTLICHEN VERZEICHNISSEN ODER ZU VERTRAGSWIDRIGEM VERHALTEN VOR"],"fraudPreCheck":{"resultType":"VERARBEITUNGSFEHLER","errorMessage":["{id:PLA0012, text:Feld muss gefüllt sein, detail:GP-Geschaeftsvorgangsreferenz}"]},"schufaReferenceId":"50273634"}

I don’t know which is the business logic for having externalCreditClass set to “X” but if it is not related to the schufa-rating response, I suggest to create a bug ticket and assign it to DXL for a deeper analysis from the development team.

Regards,
Raniero
